<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>The Future of the BBC</title></head><body><div><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="color:#9c0058; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="color:#9c0058; font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by the Commercial Broadcasters Association [FBB0072]</span></p><p style="font-size:16pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="color:#5a5758; font-family:Georgia; font-size:16pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 7pt; text-indent:4.25pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Executive Summary</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.39pt; padding-left:4.61pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">Commercial broadcasters are one of the fastest growing parts of the UK’s TV industry. The multichannel sector has doubled employment in the last decade, raised investment in UK content by 30% in the last three years, and last year grew commissioning from independent producers by 50%.</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 17pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.94pt; padding-left:3.06pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">This growth is </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">key</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt"> to the UK’s future success as a global TV hub, helping provide the critical mass the UK needs to compete with major media </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">centres</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt"> around the world. And, with many having strong international networks, multichannel broadcasters fuel exports of UK content, reinvesting income into UK production.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.86pt; padding-left:3.14pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">We </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">believe the</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt"> BBC </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">should </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">be seen within the changing landscape o</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">f the UK’s TV sector. The UK is </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">a </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">more</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt"> mixed, more global</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt"> ecology than ever before. T</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">he BBC ha</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">s a key role to play in this ecology, as do </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">commercial broadcasters</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt"> and others</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">. Maintaining a competitive market that enables a range of players to develop is </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">key</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt"> to future growth. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">We therefore welcom</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">e this inquiry</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">. O</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">ne of our </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">concerns </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">is that </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">oversight of </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">the BBC should be </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">robust and transparent, </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">in order to ensure that it does not </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">have an undue </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">market impact.</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt"> We are not convinced that oversight is </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">curre</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">ntly effective enough, as demonstrated by well-documented concer</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">n</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt"> over the neg</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">ative market impact </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">of Lonely Planet and BBC Jam</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">, the cost of the aborted DMI project, and </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">management pay</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">outs highlight</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">ed</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt"> by the NAO and </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">PAC hearing</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">We note how Management and </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">Trust have acted together in response, launch</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">ing a joint review of the BBC governance,</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">despite the </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">clear </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">requirement in the Charter for separation between the two bodies.</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.57pt; padding-left:3.43pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">We therefore</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt"> believe there is a need for </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">more robust, transparent and accountable </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">governance</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">, that</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt"> guarantees complete separation between the two bodies</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.03pt; padding-left:2.97pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">In addition</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt"> we are concerned about</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt"> recent proposals to augment certain BBC services</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">. Firstly, the Government has </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">proposed</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt"> to enhance PSB prominence requirements. While we appreciate </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">such services should</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt"> be </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">readily </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">available on </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">new p</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">latforms, we are not convinced </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">there is</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt"> a need for </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">legislation</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">, as PSB on-demand services are already widely used. We</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt"> ask the </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">Committee to call on the DCMS, as part of any forthcoming consultation, </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">to consider a) whether PSB services are already available </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">and readily discoverable </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">on on-demand platforms and b) whether extending prominence would have a negative impact on inno</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">vative new services</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.26pt; padding-left:3.74pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">he </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">Government is</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">also </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">considering enhancing PSB pro</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">minence </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">on well-established linear TV platforms. </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">This could damage investment in UK children’s content. In moving</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt"> the BBC children’s channels to the top of the Sky children’s </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">EPG section, </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">other channels </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">would move down. For these channels, EPG position helps determine income (and therefore content budgets). </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">In contrast, the BBC</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">’s income is not contingent on </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">it</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">s EPG position</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.39pt; padding-left:2.61pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">he BBC children’s channel</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt"> are already highly successful, being the most watched channels in their demographics. The Director General </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">outlined their success </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">to the Committee in October, saying:</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt"> “t</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">hese two channels are working and they’re finding their audience.”</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.03pt; padding-left:2.97pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">We</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt"> ask the Committee to call on the</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt"> DCMS</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">, as part of any consultation on these proposals, to consider </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">the impact on</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt"> investment in UK’s children’s content.</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 17pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">Separately, the BBC recently announced a raft of changes to </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">its on-demand services</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">. Taken together, these are potentially significant moves in the market and could have a negative impact on commercial services. We will be asking the Trust to investigate the market impact of these proposals fully, and ask the Committee to support our request for a full Public Value Test.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">We are </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">also </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">concerned</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">, however,</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">over the lack of transparency in the process for introducing these changes. BBC Management’s statement of 8</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt"> October</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt"> reports the</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">ir</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt"> forthcoming launch with near certainty, despite the fact they have not received Trust approval. In a highly competitive </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">online market</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">, it is vital these services are subject to full and transparent review, and that any statements about them in advance of approval reflect this. The current situation creates unnecessary uncertainty for the rest of the market, and indeed calls into question how the BBC is governed.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#d9d9d9; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 17pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The Commercial Broadcasters Association (COBA) is the industry body for multichannel broadcasters and their on-demand services in the UK. </span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><br style="page-break-before:always; clear:both" /></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><img src="data:image/png;base64,iVBORw0KGgoAAAANSUhEUgAAAjIAAAABCAYAAADEvURzAAAAAXNSR0IArs4c6QAAAARnQU1BAACxjwv8YQUAAAAJcEhZcwAADsMAAA7DAcdvqGQAAAAgSURBVEhLY2AYBaMhMBoCoyEwGgKjITAaAqMhMERDAAAIyQABxYXUSAAAAABJRU5ErkJggg==" width="562" height="1" alt="" style="margin-left:118.6pt; margin-top:314.8pt; position:absolute; z-index:0" /><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Q1 </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">What</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> should the BBC be for and what should be the purpose of public service broadcasting?</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">1.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">Commercial broadcasters in the multichannel sector are one of the fastest growing parts of the UK TV industry. The sector has doubled direct employment in the last decade, increased investment in UK content by 30% in the last three years, and increased commissioning from independent producers by 50% last year. The multichannel sector now accounts for 18% of all new UK TV production.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super"> </span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">1.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">This growth </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">fuels </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">the UK’s </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">status </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">as </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">a </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">global TV hub. The multichannel sector now has a turnover of £5 billion a year, helping provide the UK with the critical mass it needs to compete with </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">other </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">major media </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">centres</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt"> around the world. And, with </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">many having</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">strong </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">international networks, multichannel broadcasters </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">help drive exports of UK content, </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">reinvesting that income into UK production. Last year, </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">35% </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">of multichannel commissions in the UK were part funded through their international divisions.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super"> </span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">1.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">In many areas, this commercially-funded content </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">is comparable to </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">PSB content. Sky’s commitment </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">to the arts includes </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">commission</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt"> The South Bank Show, while Disney funds the production of Art Attack, historically commissioned by PSBs. But just as importantly, non PSB broadcasters add diversity. For example, according to producers body Pact, the multichannel sector commissions a substantially higher proportion of UK content from smaller producers than PSBs. </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">This creates more opportunities for SMEs in the supply base. </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">Pact’s census states that 34% of </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">multichannel spend</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt"> went on producers with a turnover of less than £25m per annum. This compares to 16% at the BBC, 8% at Channel 4, 19% at </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">Five</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt"> and 11% at ITV.</span><a name="_ftnref8"></a><a href="#_ftn8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">1.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">We therefore believe that the future of the BBC needs to be seen within the changing landscape of the UK</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">’s</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt"> TV sector. The UK is </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">a more</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt"> mixed, more global ec</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">ology than ever before. The </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">BBC ha</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">s a key role to play, as do </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">commercial broadcasters</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt"> and others</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">. Maintaining a healthy, competitive market that enables a range of players to develop is </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">key</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt"> to fut</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">ure growth, and robust governance of the BBC is key to this.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">1.5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">We comment on the nature of the BBC’s public purposes below.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Q2 </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">How</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> well has the BBC performed in the current Charter period in achieving its mission and public purposes? Are the public purposes in the current Charter the right ones? How might they change?</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">2.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">The number of the BBC’s public purposes –</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">in addition to other goals set by the Trust – can dilute the BBC’s impact </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">is at times conflicting. For example, BBC Worldwide </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">has a public purpose to </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">promote the BBC brand through its overseas channels. However, broadcasting BBC programmes on those channels, rather than selling them to third-party channels</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt"> on a commercial basis</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">risks </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">r</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">estricting</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt"> the amount of revenues </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">Worldwide</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt"> is able to return to the BBC from exploiting its IP.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">2.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">We believe that it is worth considering whether the number of overall purposes should be limited, or the priority of relevant purposes should be made clearer for each service.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Q3 What scope, scale and remit should the BBC have?</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Should the BBC’s output and services be provided to any greater or lesser degree for particular audiences?</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">What balance should be struck in what the BBC produces in-house, commissions externally and leaves entirely to others to create?</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Scope, scale and remit</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">3.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">We are concerned about proposals to augment certain BBC services</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">. Firstly, the Government has put forward proposals to enhance PSB prominence requirements. Currently, </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">PSB services </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">are entitled to privileged positions </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">o</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">n the Electronic Programme Guide </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">(EPG) </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">for TV channels. The new proposals are focused on extending the prominence of PSBs onto on-demand platforms. While we appreciate the </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">importance of </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">such services be</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">readily </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">available, we are not convinced that </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">there is a need for </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">legislation</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">, as PSB on-demand services are widely used already.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">3.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">W</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">e therefore ask the Committee to call on </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">the Government, a</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">s part of the DCMS’s forthcoming </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">consultation on these proposals, </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">to consider a) whether PSB services are already </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">readily </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">available on on-demand platforms and b) whether extending prominence in this way would have a negative impact on innovati</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">on</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">by crowding out </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">new services. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">3.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">In addition, as part of these proposals, the Government is also considering enhancing PSB pr</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">ominence </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">on well-established linear TV platforms. Proposals to take a more prescriptive definition of ‘appropriate prominence’ under the 2003 Communications Act would move the BBC children’s channels to the top of the Sky children’s section. This would have a negative impact on investment in UK children’s </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">content,</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt"> as such a move would inevitably </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">mean moving</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt"> other channels down, reducing their audience share and impacting on their content budgets. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">3.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">Over the last three years, COBA children’s channels have increased their investment in UK children’s content by 60%, to </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">nearly </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">£30m.</span><a name="_ftnref9"></a><a href="#_ftn9">[9]</a><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt"> This has gone a long way to replace declines in children’s investment </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">at commercial PSBs</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">, but this commissioning would be likely to be damaged by forcing those channels to move down the EPG. In contrast, the BBC does not depend on its EPG position to determine its income, which of course comes from the licence fee. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">3.5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">he BBC children’s channels already have privileged prominence, being entitled to the best available slots (non PSB channels go automatically to the bottom of the EPG section when launching). </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">3.6</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">P</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">erhaps most importantly, </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">however, </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">the BBC children’s channel</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt"> are already highly successful, being the most watched channels in their demographics. The Director General </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">outlined their success </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">to the Committee in October, saying:</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">“So </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">Newsround</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt"> now is not on BBC One but the figures for </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">Newsround</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt"> are growing. Likewise with Blue Peter the figures are growing, so these two channels are working and they’re finding their audience.”</span><a name="_ftnref10"></a><a href="#_ftn10">[10]</a></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">3.7</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">Anne </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">Bulford</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">, the BBC’s </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">Managing Director, Operations and Finance, </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">expanded on this</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt"> in her evidence</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">, saying: </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">“[C]</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">hildren’s</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt"> awareness of children’s channels and digital channels is very high and </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">Cbeebies</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt"> and CBBC are the first place they go, so nought to six 95% of them are aware of it and six to 12s 89% are aware of CBBC, so I think that’s very encouraging. Where the channels are, how we cross-promote them, how we take people to those channels is what’s important and everything Tony said about the app and how its broken up I think shows that content is very key and children love it and they find it and they come to it.”</span><a name="_ftnref11"></a><a href="#_ftn11">[11]</a></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">3.8</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">We therefore ask the Committee to call on the Government, as part of any consultation on these proposals, to consider </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">fully the impact of investment i</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">n UK’s children’s content.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">3.9</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">Separately, the BBC recently announced a raft of changes to </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">on-demand services</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">, including extending the </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">iPlayer</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">catch-up window from seven to 30 days, premiering content on the </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">i</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">P</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">layer</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt"> before it has been broadcast on linear channels, and a download</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">to</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">own service, BBC Store. Taken together, these are potentially significant moves in the market and could have a negative impact on commercial services. </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">They also entail, in our view, substantial changes to the current service. </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">We will be asking the Trust to investigate the market impact of these proposals fully, and ask the Committee to support our request for a full Public Value Test.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">3.10</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">However, the manner in which these services were announced, without full scrutiny by the Trust, does also in our view raise questions over the oversight of the BBC, as we outline in response to Question 7.</span><span style="color:#9c0058; font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Q4 </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">How</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> have the BBC’s commercial activities during the current Charter fitted with the BBC’s public purposes and have they achieved an adequate return for licence fee payers? What should be the aims, scope and scale of such activities beyond 2016?</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">4.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">It is of concern that the BBC’s reigning in of Lonely Planet and also BBC Jam came relatively late, after widespread concerns were raised, including by this Committee, and, as a result, at considerable additional cost to the licence fee payer, as well as after unnecessary uncertainty in the wider market.</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Q5 </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">What</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> role should the BBC play in developing technology and new ways of distributing content?</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">5.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">Our concern here is that the BBC should not have an undue impact on the market. We are not convinced that the BBC governance system is robust enough, as we outline in response to Question 7.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Q6 </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">How</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> should the BBC be funded beyond 2016?</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Is there a case for distributing funding for public service content more widely beyond the BBC? What comparisons can be made with the provision of public serv</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">ice content in other countries?</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">6.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">Funding is already being distributed beyond the BBC, </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">for example to support S4C</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">Whether licence fee funding should be distributed to other parties is a major debate that may warrant discussion during the Charter renewal process.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Q7 </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">How</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> should the BBC be governed, regulated and held accountable beyond 2016? In a constantly evolving communications environment, does a 10-year Royal Charter and Agreement with the Secretary of State, together, provide the most appropriate constitutional framework for the BBC?</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">7.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">The Charter clearly requires separation between</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt"> Management and the BBC Trust, </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">stating</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt"> that: </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">“The members of the Trust and the members of the Board shall never act together as a single corporate body.”</span><a name="_ftnref12"></a><a href="#_ftn12">[12]</a><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">7.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">The Charter goes on to say that: “The Trust must maintain its independence of the Executive Board.”</span><a name="_ftnref13"></a><a href="#_ftn13">[13]</a></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">7.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">Yet Management and Trust have acted together on issues of the highest importance. Most recently, in the wake of the critical NAO report and PAC hearing, the Director General and the Chairman of the Trust wrote jointly to the Secretary of State for Culture, Media &amp; Sport to promise a review of the BBC’s governance.</span><a name="_ftnref14"></a><a href="#_ftn14">[14]</a><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt"> This letter promised that the Director General and the Chairman “will together lead this piece of work, drawing on internal resourc</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">es from both parts of the BBC.”</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">7.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">We view this joint approach as raising serious questions over the effectiveness of the Charter’s requirement for separation, and as particularly ill-</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">advised as it is a review of </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">the BBC’s governance systems. Put simply, the body being governed is jointly leading the review into how it is governed. This is a scenario </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">we cannot </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">envisage </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">happening </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">for any other UK broadcaster, yet the BBC, with its privilege of public funding, should be held to the highest standards. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">7.5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">We also note that this form of joint response</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt"> has occurred before, when Management and the BBC Trust issued a joint response to </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">Ofcom’s</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt"> second review of Public Service Broadcasting (which was looking at granting some of the licence fee to other services).</span><a name="_ftnref15"></a><a href="#_ftn15">[15]</a></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="color:#9c0058; font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">7.6</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">In addition, as we have noted previously, the way BBC Management announced changes to the </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">iPlayer</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt"> recently raises questions as to the level of oversight that the Trust has. The changes to the </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">iPlayer</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt"> could have negative consequences on the rest of the market. Yet Management made </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">public announcements regarding the new </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">iPlayer</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt"> features as if they were a near certainty,</span><a name="_ftnref16"></a><a href="#_ftn16">[16]</a><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt"> despite the fact that they had not received Trust approval. In a highly competitive commercial online marketplace, where UK media companies are striving to gain even a minimal foothold, this creates unnecessary uncertainty, and calls into question how the BBC is governed.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">7.7</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">To restore the confidence of industry, not to mention the public, BBC governance will require a far greater level of transparency</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">, robustness and clarity – and crucially there must be a clear and guaranteed separation between Management and whichever body oversees it.</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt"> It may also require greater resources</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt"> being allocated to the oversight body</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">, in order to ensure it</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt"> is able to perform this function properly</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Constitutional framework</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">7.8</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">The Charter and Agreement are sufficiently high level for the BBC to have an appropriate level of flexibility in most areas. </span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="color:#9c0058; font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="color:#9c0058; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:10pt">Building a Global TV Hub: Multichannel broadcasters and the UK’s global competitiveness, Communications Chambers for COBA, November 2013</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:10pt"> </span><a href="http://downloads.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/Maria-Miller-letter-sep13.pdf"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://downloads.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/Maria-Miller-letter-sep13.pdf</span></a></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:10pt">BBC Royal Charter</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:10pt">, Section 9</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn4"></a><a href="#_ftnref4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:10pt"> </span><a href="http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201314/cmselect/cmcumeds/uc730/uc73001.htm"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201314/cmselect/cmcumeds/uc730/uc73001.htm</span></a></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn5"></a><a href="#_ftnref5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:10pt"> </span><a href="http://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/latestnews/2013/dg-iplayer.html"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/latestnews/2013/dg-iplayer.html</span></a></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn6"></a><a href="#_ftnref6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:10pt">Building a Global TV Hub: Multichannel broadcasters and the 